Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: My motivation stems from the observation that while prior work has explored affirmative paraphrasing (Paper 2) and posterior consistency under perturbation (Papers 1 and 3), none have explicitly framed *affirmative reinterpretation* as a form of *semantic regularization*—a structured, training-time intervention that stabilizes model predictions not just against surface-level noise, but against *logical inversions* such as negation. Negation flips meaning without altering syntax drastically, making it a particularly insidious source of model failure. I propose treating automatically generated affirmative reconstructions not merely as data augmentation, but as *semantic anchors* during training—forcing the model to maintain consistent latent representations between a negated sentence and its positive semantic counterpart. This differs from existing methods in two key ways: (1) Unlike consistency regularization based on data augmentation (Paper 1), which focuses on invariance to visual or syntactic transformations, ours enforces invariance to *semantic polarity shifts*, using affirmations as counterfactual guides; (2) Unlike posterior differential regularization (Paper 3), which compares clean vs. noisy inputs, we compare logically opposed yet semantically linked inputs—negated and affirmed versions—and regularize their representation divergence using f-divergences grounded in information theory. Crucially, our method integrates automatic affirmation generation via pre-trained T5 or LLM-based paraphrasers into the training loop, creating a dynamic, self-supervised signal that teaches models to decouple negation markers from core semantics. This creates a more robust internal representation space where meaning is preserved across polarity changes—a capability essential for real-world NLP systems exposed to complex linguistic variation.

